04584nam a22006615i 9780824893095DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222022hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a2022010462  a97808248930957 a10.1515/97808248930952doi  a(DE-B1597)635236  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI00aBQ8822b.C37 2022 4aBQ8822b.C37 2022 7aREL0070102bisacsh04a299.5/6223/eng/202203151 aCarter, Caleb Swift, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Path into the Mountains :bShugendō and Mount Togakushi /cCaleb Swift Carter. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b13 illustrations, 2 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Style -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Revisiting the History of Shugendō -- tPart 1 Before Shugendō -- t1 Converting the Demon with Nine Heads -- t2 Emboldened Narratives -- t3 Contested Boundaries -- t4 Mountain Asceticism before Shugendō -- tPart 2 Transmitting Shugendō -- t5 A Mountain School on the Move -- t6 A Path of Entry -- tPart 3 Shugendō, Localized and Nationalized -- t7 Pilgrims, Dragon Worship, and New Kami -- t8 Embedding Shugendō into a Regional Landscape -- t9 Climbing for Laymen, Restrictions for Women -- t10 Ancient Lore for a Recent Tradition -- tEpilogue -- tEast Asian Names and Terms -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShugendō has been an object of fascination among scholars and the general public, yet its historical development remains an enigma. This book offers a provocative reexamination of the social, economic, and spiritual terrain from which this mountain religious system arose. Caleb Carter traces Shugendō through the mountains of Togakushi (Nagano Prefecture), while situating it within the religious landscape of medieval and early modern Japan. His is the first major study to view Shugendō as a self-conscious religious system—something that was historically emergent but conceptually distinct from the prevailing Buddhist orders of medieval Japan. Beyond Shugendō, his work rethinks a range of issues in the history of Japanese religions, including exclusionary policies toward women, the formation of Shintō, and religion at the social and geographical margins of the Japanese archipelago.Carter takes a new tack in the study of religions by tracking three recurrent and intersecting elements—institution, ritual, and narrative. Examination of origin accounts, temple records, gazetteers, and iconography from Togakushi demonstrates how practitioners implemented storytelling, new rituals and festivals, and institutional measures to merge Shugendō with their mountain’s culture while establishing social legitimacy and economic security. Indicative of early modern trends, the case of Mount Togakushi reveals how Shugendō moved from a patchwork of regional communities into a translocal system of national scope, eventually becoming Japan’s signature mountain religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aShugen (Sect)xHistory. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / History.2bisacsh  aAsia religion.  aBuddhism.  aJapan.  aJapanese religion.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780824893095?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824893095423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824893095/original  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK